  <h1>About SeveranceCalc</h1>

  <p>
    severancepayestimator.com &mdash; SeveranceCalc &mdash; is a free severance-pay resource maintained by The Click Lab. Our Severance Pay Estimator and guides help departing employees understand what a realistic severance range looks like based on years of service, salary, industry, and the reason for separation &mdash; before they've spoken with HR, signed anything, or hired an attorney. Most people encounter a severance offer once or twice in an entire career, which isn't enough to build any real intuition for what's standard, what's negotiable, and what's simply a lowball number dressed up in formal language. The Site exists to close that gap with a plain-English starting point, not a substitute for legal or financial advice.
  </p>

  <h2>What we do</h2>
  <p>
    We translate severance-pay practice &mdash; industry benchmark formulas, WARN Act notice-and-pay obligations, tax treatment, and separation-agreement terms &mdash; into a free calculator and a set of practical guides. Every page is reviewed by our <a href="/editorial/">editorial team</a> against BLS compensation data, SHRM and WorldatWork benchmarking surveys, and publicly disclosed separation terms. The calculator estimates a pay range using the weeks-of-pay-per-year-of-service formula most U.S. employers actually use, then adjusts for the reason for separation and employment type &mdash; the factors that most often move a real offer above or below the generic benchmark.
  </p>

  <h2>Who this calculator is for</h2>
  <p>
    Most visitors fall into a few groups: employees who've just received a layoff notice or separation agreement and want to know whether the number in front of them is reasonable before they sign or negotiate; HR professionals and people managers who want a quick benchmark check against their own company's policy; career coaches and recruiters helping clients think through a transition; and people who are simply trying to understand what they'd be entitled to if their role were ever eliminated. We built the Site around these use cases, which is why every guide leads with a plain-English answer before it gets into formula or statutory detail.
  </p>

  <h2>How the estimate is built</h2>
  <p>
    The full mechanics &mdash; the base weeks-per-year formula, the industry benchmark rates, the reason-for-separation multiplier, and the employment-type adjustment &mdash; are documented on our <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>, including the underlying BLS, SHRM, and WorldatWork survey data we draw from. At a high level: the calculator starts from an industry-standard base rate, adjusts it for whether the separation was a layoff, a reduction in force, a mutual agreement, or performance-based, and factors in full-time, exempt, or part-time status. Confirming what a specific offer letter, employment contract, or state law actually guarantees requires reading the actual documents &mdash; something only you, your HR department, or an employment attorney can do.
  </p>

  <h2>What we don't do</h2>
  <p>
    We don't provide legal, tax, or financial advice, and nothing on this Site creates an attorney-client relationship. Actual severance outcomes depend on facts a calculator can't see: the specific language in your offer letter or employment contract, any collective bargaining agreement, company policy, state law, and how hard you negotiate. We also don't evaluate individual severance offers, review specific separation agreements, or recommend particular attorneys or law firms. For your specific situation, see our <a href="/contact/">contact page</a> for guidance on what to do next.
  </p>

  <h2>Editorial standards</h2>
  <p>
    Every guide and reference page is written from primary sources &mdash; BLS and SHRM compensation surveys, WARN Act text and regulations, IRS guidance on severance taxation, and publicly filed separation agreements &mdash; and reviewed before publication. We don't publish thin content: each page is meant to answer a specific question a departing employee would actually ask, with enough detail to be useful when a real decision is on the table. Our full editorial workflow, contributor backgrounds, and sourcing policy are on the <a href="/editorial/">editorial team page</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>How we make money</h2>
  <p>
    Display advertising via Google AdSense. We don't sell reader data or accept paid placements, and no law firm, outplacement provider, or HR consultancy pays for placement or a favorable mention anywhere on the Site. See our <a href="/privacy/">privacy policy</a> for details on data handling.
  </p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>
    Questions, corrections, or feedback: see our <a href="/contact/">contact page</a>.
  </p>
